{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17497049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17497049"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1464"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1464"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.51,0.18,0.05,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114881"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1464"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96887"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"1147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"1363"},{"type":"tags","id":"2932"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8332"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44773"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114881"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of vague upper abdominal pain radiating to his back with associated nausea. He has lost 10kg during this time. He feels thirsty, is passing more urine than usual, and is getting up at night to void. He has no significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications and has a 10 pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 75/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood glucose level: 16.0 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 150 g/L (120-170)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 11 \u00d710\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 450 \u00d710\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHbA1c: 12% (4-6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine dipstick shows ++ glucose without protein or blood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA plain abdominal CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the next most appropriate imaging modality for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound abdomen","Pancreas-protocol CT abdomen and pelvis with contrast","Endoscopic ultrasonography guided biopsy","MRI abdomen","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features suggestive of pancreatic cancer: vague upper abdominal pain radiating to the back, significant weight loss, and new-onset diabetes mellitus (evidenced by polyuria, polydipsia, nocturia, and markedly elevated HbA1c). The plain CT scan shows a necrotic mass at the junction of the body and tail of the pancreas, further supporting this diagnosis (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreas-protocol CT abdomen and pelvis with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This specialised CT technique uses specific timing of contrast administration and image acquisition to optimize visualisation of the pancreas and surrounding vasculature. It is the gold standard initial imaging modality for staging pancreatic cancer and determining resectability by assessing the relationship of the tumor to adjacent vascular structures. This information is crucial for treatment planning and determining whether the patient is a surgical candidate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is less sensitive than CT for pancreatic lesions and would be a step backward in the diagnostic workup, given that a plain CT has already identified a pancreatic mass. Ultrasound has limited ability to visualise the pancreas due to overlying bowel gas and patient body habitus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic ultrasonography guided biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is used for tissue diagnosis of pancreatic masses and is particularly valuable for small lesions. However, it is not the next step after identifying a mass on plain CT. This procedure would typically be performed after a pancreas-protocol CT has determined the extent of disease, and when tissue diagnosis is needed before initiating treatment, particularly if neoadjuvant therapy is being considered for borderline resectable disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E may provide additional characterisation of pancreatic lesions, particularly cystic ones, but is not the standard next step after identifying a solid pancreatic mass on CT. MRI is sometimes used as a problem-solving tool when CT findings are equivocal or to better evaluate the biliary and pancreatic ducts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily a therapeutic procedure for biliary obstruction in pancreatic cancer, rather than a diagnostic tool. It would be indicated if the patient had jaundice or cholangitis from biliary obstruction, which is not present in this case with a body/tail pancreatic mass. ERCP carries significant risks including pancreatitis and is not used as a routine diagnostic procedure when less invasive options are available.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pancreatic cancer should be suspected in patients with vague abdominal pain, weight loss, and new-onset diabetes mellitus.","Pancreas-protocol CT scan with contrast is the initial imaging modality of choice for staging suspected pancreatic cancer.","Tissue diagnosis is not always required before surgery for resectable pancreatic cancer unless neoadjuvant therapy is being considered."],"references":["Shrikhande SV, Barreto SG, Goel M, Arya S. Multi-modality imaging of Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma: a review of the literature. HPB (Oxford) 2012; 14: 658-668. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3461371/","Barreto SG. Pancreatic cancer. In: Surgical Diseases of the Pancreas and Biliary Tree. Edited by Barreto SG, Windsor J. Springer Nature. Singapore 2018. Available at: https://researchnow.flinders.edu.au/en/publications/surgical-diseases-of-the-pancreas-and-biliary-tree","Hartwig W, Schneider L, Diener MK, Bergmann F, B\u00fcchler MW, Werner J. Preoperative tissue diagnosis for tumours of the pancreas. Br J Surg 2009; 96: 5-20. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19016272/","Barreto, S., \u0026 Windsor, J. A. (2021). Preoperative Management of Jaundice. In K. Soreide, \u0026 S. Stattner (Eds.), Textbook of Pancreatic Cancer: Principles and Practice of Surgical Oncology (pp. 631-648). Springer-Nature. Available at: https://researchnow.flinders.edu.au/en/publications/preoperative-management-of-jaundice"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96887"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1464"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19613"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22127"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19613"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4244dc2b-629f-430f-b121-366cc569356c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4244dc2b-629f-430f-b121-366cc569356c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":785,"height":638}},{"type":"media","id":"22127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22127"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/wOQs7Nsc6HdumiGljuJG654jAWEv4T.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/wOQs7Nsc6HdumiGljuJG654jAWEv4T.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":785,"height":638}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96887"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T12:16:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T12:17:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1464"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114881"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\